In order to display archived documents in a Digital Archiving store, it is necessary to **perform a search**. The search will return any documents that comply with the selected search criteria and display them in the documents area.

> Note

The currently displayed documents are always the result of a performed search. If no search has been performed yet, the documents area will be empty.

There are two types of search criteria:

**Document categories**: Logical containers for digitally archived documents of the same type. All documents from a selected category will be considered for the search.

**Document attributes**: Criteria used to store and search document metadata based on an index and a logical operator. The search behavior depends on the logical operator (see).[Digital Archiving Stores - Managing Access Endpoints#Managing document attributes](/doxee-platform/docs/digital-archive-developer-guide-manage-access-endpoints#managing-document-attributes).

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

The search criteria can be entered in the Criteria area on the left side of the screen:

- Include or exclude Document categories from search by toggling or untoggling them in the Criteria area.

> Warning

It is necessary to include at least one Document category in the search in order to return any documents.

-  Enter search parameters for Document attributes in the Criteria area.

> Note

The accepted values depend on the data type of the index with which the Document attribute has been configured (see [Digital Archiving Stores - Managing Indexes](/doxee-platform/docs/digital-archive-developer-guide-manage-indexes)). The data type is indicated by an icon next to the Document attribute field:

**Icon**

**Description**

**Value**

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

String

Alphanumerical (max. 250 characters)

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

Number

Numerical

**Min and max search** 

It is possible to search for the lowest or highest value of a numerical index, regardless of which 

logical operator is configured for the index.

Click the drop-down arrow in the input field and select **Min value** or** Max value**. The configured logical operator of the index will be ignored for the search query.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

The min or max value operator will be applied to the result of all other search parameters. For example, if a string and date parameters have been entered along with a min value numerical search parameter, the result will be the lowest numerical value that also matches the string and date search parameters.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

Date

YYYY-MM-DD

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

Time

YYYY-MM-DD hh:mm:ss

- *(optional)* Add another search query input box (maximum: 1000).

> Warning

When the user opens multiple search query boxes and enters multiple different values for the same document attribute, the search uses **OR** logic to return documents.

Duplicate search results will be displayed only once, for example if the same value is entered in two search queries, the duplicate value is ignored.

- Click the *Search* button to perform the search.

> Warning

The default maximum number of displayed search results is 1000. Search results are sorted in descending order by their date of creation. 

All documents which meet the search criteria will be returned. This also applies to Digital Archiving stores which have been configured for versioning.

## Search by CSV file
Instead of entering all search parameters manually, it's possible to upload a CSV file with multiple search queries. Each row in the CSV file represents one search query.

- Click&nbsp;![](data:image/png;base64,) **Import queries from CSV file**.

- Select the CSV file from the filepicker dialog and click *Done*.

- Click the *Search* button to perform the search.

The Criteria area is populated with multiple search query boxes containing the inputs provided in the CSV file. The search uses **OR** logic to return documents.

The CSV file must respect the following requirements to be considered valid:

- Must contain a header row with aliases that match the document attributes

- Separator must be a semicolon ;

- Each row represents one search query and is displayed as a search query box in the Criteria area

- Date format: YYYY-MM-dd

- Datetime format (in local time): YYYY-MM-dd HH:mm:ss

- Minimum and maximum values must be prefixed by $MIN and $MAX operators

The search by CSV file behaves as follows:

- Headers which don't match the document attribute aliases are ignored by the search

- Invalid values are displayed with a warning and the **Search** button in the Criteria area is disabled

- If the Criteria area already contains active search query boxes with inputs, it is not replaced by the search queries from the CSV file If the Criteria area contains empty search query boxes, they are replaced by the search queries from the CSV file

- Only the first 1000 query rows from the CSV will be processed

- If the file contains more than 1000 query rows, a warning is displayed

- If the Criteria area contains 1000 active search query boxes, the ![](data:image/png;base64,) **Import queries from CSV file **button is disabled
